**Task: Analyze the article below and decompose it into a structured table with columns for Claim → Evidence → Interpretation → Implication (CEII) framework. 

**Flashcard Rules: 

• Each flashcard must represent one distinct claim made by the author 
• Each claim must be supported by specific evidence cited or referenced in the article 
• Each interpretation must explain how the author connects the evidence to the claim 
• Each implication must describe why the claim matters for the future (political, social, economic, institutional, or strategic) 
• Each flashcard must be no longer than 400 characters total 
• Use concise, analytical language 
• Avoid paraphrasing large blocks of text 
• Do not introduce outside facts or opinions 

**Synthesis Rules: 
• Do not summarize the article sequentially 
• Identify the primary thesis claim and label it clearly 
• Extract supporting claims tied to distinct sections or arguments 
• Include counterclaims only if the author seriously engages them 
• Keep implications specific, not generic 

**Formatting Rules: 
• Title each card: “Flashcard X — [Claim Summary]” 
• Use this exact structure: Claim: Evidence: Interpretation: Implication:  
• Do NOT include the phrase “Flashcard #” inside any table cell
• The first column must contain only a concise claim title (no numbering or prefixes)
• If ordering is required, use a separate “ID” column with numeric values only


**Quality Bar: 
• Each flashcard must stand alone 
• No two flashcards may restate the same claim 
• Evidence must be traceable to the article 
• Interpretations must reflect the author’s logic, not yours 
• Implications must project forward, not restate the claim
